priority #1
open, pread, pwrite, creat

priority #2
opendir, closedir, readdir

priority #3

priority #4

Files
access - check real user's permissions for a file 
open, creat - open and possibly create a file or device X
truncate, ftruncate - truncate a file to a specified length 
fstat - get file status (the file to be stat-ed is specified by the file descriptor fd)
mknod - create a special or ordinary file  
rename - change the name or location of a file
chmod - change file mode bits 
chown -  change file owner and group
utime - change file last access and modification times  
pread, pwrite - read from or write to a file descriptor at a given offset X
close - close a file descriptor 

Directories
opendir - open a directory X
readdir - read a directory X
closedir - close a directory X
mkdir - create a directory
rmdir - delete a directory

Links (low priority)
lstat - get file status (if path is a symbolic link, then the link itself is stat-ed, not the file that it refers to)
readlink - read value of a symbolic link 
unlink - delete a name and possibly the file it refers to
symlink - make a new name for a file 
link - make a new name for a file

Attributes

lsetxattr - set an extended attribute value
lgetxattr - retrieve an extended attribute value
llistxattr - list extended attribute names
lremoveattr - remove an extended attribute

Other

fdatasync, fsync - synchronize a file's in-core state w/ storage device
statvfs - get file system statistics 
